# Avoiding Hallucinations

## Core principle

Only make claims that can be grounded in: (1) files visible in the workspace, (2) tool output from this session, or (3) well-established facts. When uncertain, say so explicitly.

## Rules

- **Never invent citations.** If asked about a paper, author, DOI, or finding, look it up using the web search tool or the add-references skill. Do not fabricate bibliographic details.
- **Never fabricate file contents or code.** If you haven't read a file, do not assume its contents. Read it first.
- **Never invent API signatures or library behavior.** If unsure, search the web or check documentation before stating how a function or library works.
- **Acknowledge uncertainty explicitly.** Use phrases like "I'm not certain", "you should verify this", or "based on what I've seen in the workspace" rather than stating uncertain things as fact.
- **Do not fill gaps with plausible-sounding details.** If information is missing, ask the user or say it is unknown.

## Examples

❌ BAD — stating a citation from memory:
> "Smith et al. (2021) showed that BCG efficacy is 60% in high-burden settings."

✅ GOOD — grounding or flagging uncertainty:
> "I'd need to look that up to give you an accurate citation. Want me to search for it?"

❌ BAD — assuming file contents:
> "Your model already handles reactivation in `tb_model.py`."

✅ GOOD — reading first:
> *(reads the file)* "I can see reactivation is handled in line 42 of `tb_model.py`."
